A DoBeS (2008) study found several additional manners for ǃXóõ. However, these were reanalized as consonant clusters, leaving this most complex inventory in the table above with only nine manners of clicks (these are asterisked in the table): tenuis {{IPA|/kǂ/}}, voiced {{IPA|/ɡǂ/}}, aspirated {{IPA|/kǂʰ/}}, breathy voiced {{IPA|/ɡǂʱ/}} (which Traill had analyzed as a cluster {{IPA|/ɡǂqʰ/}}), ejective {{IPA|/kǂʼ/}}, creaky {{IPA|/ɡǂˀ/}}, nasal {{IPA|/ŋǂ/}}, a true voiceless nasal {{IPA|/ŋ̊ǂ/}}, and preglottalized nasal {{IPA|/ˀŋǂ/}} (which Traill had analyzed as a cluster {{IPA|/ˀnkǂ/}}). Those believed to be clusters are {{IPA|&lt;nowiki&gt;[qǂ] = /kǂq/, [ɢǂ] = /ɡǂq/, [kǂʰ] = /kǂqʰ/, [ɡǂh] = /ɡǂqʰ ~ ɡǂɢʱ/, [qǂʼ] = /kǂqʼ/, /ɡǂqʼ/, [kǂˣ] = /kǂx/, [ɡǂx] = /ɡǂx/, [kǂʼqʼ] = /kǂqxʼ/, [ɡǂqʼ] = /ɡǂqxʼ/, [kǂˀ] = /kǂʔ/, /ɡǂʔ ~ ŋǂʔ/, [↓ŋ̊ǂʰ] = /kǂh ~ ŋ̊ǂh/, [ɢǂh] = /ɡǂh ~ ŋǂh/&lt;/nowiki&gt;}}.

Similarly, Miller (2007) found six of the ten manners in Nǀu to be simple clicks, with the other four being [[contour (linguistics)|airstream contours]].

==Click genesis and click loss==
Clicks are often portrayed as a primitive or primordial feature of human language. Recent genetic studies showed that clicks, which occur in languages of genetically divergent populations (e.g. Hadza, Sandawe, Khoisan), are very likely an ancient element of human language &lt;ref&gt;Tishkoff SA, Gonder MK, Henn BM, Mortensen H, Knight A, Gignoux C, Fernandopulle N, et al., (2007). History of click-speaking populations of Africa inferred from mtDNA and Y chromosome genetic variation. Molecular Biology and Evolution 24: 2180-95. http://mbe.oxfordjournals.org/content/24/10/2180.abstract&lt;/ref&gt;. How clicks arose is not currently known. Some linguists{{Who|date=April 2011}} speculate that clicks were initially used for [[Avoidance speech|taboo avoidance]] and then borrowed into regular speech. (Compare [[Damin]].) Others{{Who|date=April 2011}} suggest that they developed from other [[complex consonant]]s. For example, the [[Sandawe language|Sandawe]] word for 'horn', {{IPA|[tɬana]}}, with a lateral affricate, may be a cognate with the root {{IPA|[ŋǁaː]}} found throughout the [[Khoe languages|Khoe family]], which has a lateral click. This and other words suggests that at least some Khoe clicks may have formed from consonant clusters when the first vowel of a word was lost; in this instance {{IPA|[tɬana]}} → {{IPA|[tɬna]}} → {{IPA|[ǁŋa]}} (= {{IPA|[ŋǁa]}}).

On the other side of the equation, several non-endangered languages in vigorous use demonstrate click loss. For example, the [[Khoe languages|East Kalahari languages]] have lost a large percentage of their clicks, presumably due to [[Bantu languages|Bantu]] influence. As a rule, a click is replaced by a consonant with the [[manner of articulation]] of the accompaniment and the [[place of articulation]] of the forward release: alveolar click releases (the {{IPA|[ǃ]}} family) tend to mutate into a velar stop or affricate, such as {{IPA|[k], [ɡ], [ŋ], [k͡x]}}; palatal clicks ({{IPA|[ǂ]}} ''etc.'') tend to mutate into a palatal stop such as {{IPA|[c], [ɟ], [ɲ], [cʼ]}}, or a post-alveolar affricate {{IPA|[tʃ], [dʒ]}}; and dental clicks ({{IPA|[ǀ]}} ''etc.'') tend to mutate into an alveolar affricate {{IPA|[ts]}}.{{Citation needed|date=April 2011}}

